<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-09-06T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-09-06T16:00:00-05:00" n="797" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d797">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">825.00 Revolutions/27: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Culbertson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-06T17:00:00-04:00">September 6, 1931—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 7:20 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>110. The fleet has returned to Coquimbo after capturing a Chilean
                            commercial vessel carrying some supplies. All coastwise traffic has <pb facs="1028" n="914" xml:id="pg_914"/> been suspended and Valparaiso
                            is filled with troops. Our consular office reports no damage to American
                            commercial interests as a result of the fighting in Talcahuano. The
                            Government has called for volunteers and certain reserve officers have
                            been ordered to report for duty.</p>
                        <p>Repeated to Lima.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Culbertson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>